Citations
Date: 17/3/1860
Source: Nelson Examiner and New Zealand Chronicle
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: Thus, an Otago colonist going to Auckland would do so at a great risk to his private interests, because he is 700 miles away from home, and his house might be burnt down, his sheep scabbed, or his bills dishonoured for a fortnight before he would know anything about it; and then, if he wished to rush to the scene of disaster, he would have a long and expensive journey before him, always supposing that he could obtain leave.
